    # [Scene: Glass Conference Room | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, optimistic piano undercurrent]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmur of the municipal building, occasional distant gull]
    "You come in carrying the momentum of a choice you made back in the hall: work from the inside, bend municipal leverage toward fairer outcomes. The conference room smells of warm coffee and recycled paper; faint"
    "salt rides the ventilation like an old habit. Samir meets you at the threshold with a stack of annotated plans and a tired, genuine smile—someone who has learned how to make patience productive."
    show samir_hale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_hale "You're on time. Liora's running a little behind; thought we'd start sketching the amendments anyway."
    "You set your notebook on the table, fingers brushing the leather where tide charts are tucked. The notebook is heavier than it looks—filled with the neighborhood's margins and the small, stubborn proof that places can be"
    "measured in human terms, not just metric columns. You feel steadier than you expected. Hope, in this room, is a kind of calm work: drafting language, parsing obligations, finding the hinge between engineering and care."
    show mira_solace at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "Samir, I want the pilot clause to force community oversight—no post-hoc consultations. If Aegis gets a go-ahead, there has to be an accountability mechanism baked in."
    "Samir thumbs through his notes, eyes flicking to a highlighted section."

    samir_hale "I've pulled precedent from coastal codes elsewhere. There's room to require a neighborhood advisory panel to sign off on certain lift-and-retrofit thresholds. It would be nonbinding in some places, but binding language can be inserted if we attach municipal funding contingencies."
    "Liora Kade arrives, precise, composed; she carries a tablet like armor. The air shifts a degree—less personal warmth, more measured authority. She sets the tablet down, taps a schematic into view: a series of monolithic panels meant to reframe the shoreline."
    show liora_kade at center:
        zoom 0.7

    liora_kade "I appreciate the urgency you bring—Mira. Scale matters. If we don't move quickly with a unified wall, we risk catastrophic failure and economic fallout. We can implement safeguards, but we can't let every local preference stall the system."
    "You listen. Her voice is even and persuasive; it carries the weight of someone used to markets and memoranda. You know, without needing to parse past meetings, that she'll mean well in her own register. Her empathy is present but channeled through efficiency."

    mira_solace "You want speed, too—fast enough to stop the worst storms—but not at the erasure of places that are people's kin. The technical fix that leaves resentment and displacement in its wake is not a fix at all. Pivoting Aegis toward conditional, community-anchored implementation would be a real victory."
    "The conversation threads into the actual mechanics: funding tranches, conditional permits, retrofitting credits, relocation grants indexed to tenure and community need. Samir plays the mediator, naming what the municipality can insert as legal levers. Liora counters"
    "with delivery timetables and bonding requirements. You push in the places that matter—protections for small enterprises, stipulations for cultural preservation, enforceable grievance procedures."

    liora_kade "A contingency fund tied to bond issuance—fine. But we need an operational timetable that contractors can meet. If we make the advisory body a stopgap on every signature, construction stalls and costs balloon."

    mira_solace "Then let's make the advisory body procedural, not obstructive. Clear milestones, maximum response windows, capacity support. Make it part of the schedule so it speeds better decisions by surfacing conflicts early—not later."
    "Samir nods, relieved: the kind of compromise that moves both governance and people forward."

    samir_hale "We can draft an adaptive timeline: milestones at thirty, ninety, and two-hundred-seventy days where community input triggers specific, funded response actions, not open-ended vetoes."
    "A pause holds like a breath. Liora studies the page, then taps a line on her tablet."

    liora_kade "If we attach municipal performance incentives—tiered subsidies for community-led retrofit teams—then contractors can plan around both speed and participation. It preserves schedule and widens buy-in."
    "You allow a small, steady smile to surface. This is the shape of leverage: offering a system incentives to adopt equitable practices. It isn't everything you'd hope for, but it bends the arc."
    hide samir_hale
    hide mira_solace
    hide liora_kade

